term.definition: A linear transformation $T : \mathbb{R}^{n} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^{m}$ is *one-to-one* if for all $\vec{b} \in \mathbb{R}^{m}$ there is at most one (possibly no) $\vec{x} \in \mathbb{R}^{n}$ so that $T(\vec{x}) = \vec{b}$

term.word: If $V_{1}$ and $V_{2}$ are in $\mathbb{R}^{4}$ and $V_{2}$ is not a scalar multiple of $V_{1}$ then {$V_{1}, V_{2}$} is linearly independent
term.definition:
False

the vector $V_{1}$ could be the zero vector

term.word: Suppose A is a $5 \times 7$ matrix. How many pivot columns must A have if its columns span? $\mathbb{R}^{5}$?
If a set in set of $\mathbb{R}^{n}$ is linearly​ dependent, then the set contains more vectors than there are entries in each vector.
term.definition: False. There exists a set in set of real numbers $\mathbb{R}^{n}$ that is linearly dependent and contains n vectors. One example is a set in $\mathbb{R}^{2}$ consisting of two vectors where one of the vectors is a scalar multiple of the other.

term.word: If x and y are linearly​ independent, and if z is in Span{x,y}​, then Span{x,y,z} is linearly dependent.
term.definition: True. Since z is in Span {x,y,z} is a linear combination of x and y. Since z is a linear combination of x and y​, the set Span{x,y,z} is linearly dependent.

term.word: If a set contains fewer vectors than there are entries in the​ vectors, then the set is linearly independent.
term.definition:
False. 

There exists a set that contains fewer vectors than there are entries in the vectors that is linearly dependent. One example is a set consisting of two vectors where one of the vectors is a scalar multiple of the other vector.

term.word: Two vectors are linearly dependent if and only if they lie on a line through the origin.
term.definition:
True. 

Two vectors are linearly dependent if one of the vectors is a multiple of the other. Two such vectors will lie on the same line through the origin.

term.word: A homogeneous equation is always consistent.
term.definition: True. A homogenous equation can be written in the form $Ax = 0$​, where A is an $m \times n$ matrix and 0 is the zero vector in set of real numbers R Superscript m. Such a system $Ax = 0$ always has at least one​ solution, namely, $x = 0$. Thus a homogenous equation is always consistent.

term.word:
Let A be a $3 \times 3$ matrix with two pivot positions

Does $Ax = b$ have at least one solution for every possible b?
term.definition:
No

A has one free variable. To have atleast one solution for every possible b, there must be a pivot in every column -- no free vars.

term.word: If one row in an echelon form of an augmented matrix is \begin{bmatrix}0&0&0&5&0\end{bmatrix} ​, then the associated linear system is inconsistent.
term.definition:
False

 The indicated row corresponds to the equation $5x_{4} = 0$, which does not by itself make the system inconsistent.

term.word:
Let A be a $3 \times 3$ matrix with two pivot positions

Does $Ax = 0$ have a non trivial solution?
term.definition:
Yes

Since A has 2 pivots, there is one free var. So $Ax = 0$ has a non trivial solution

term.word: The solution set of $Ax = b$ is the set of all vectors of the form $w = p + v_{h}$ is any solution of the equation $Ax = 0$
term.definition:
False
False. The solution set could be empty. The statement is only true when the equation $Ax = b$ is consistent for some given b​, and there exists a vector p such that p is a solution.

term.word: The equation $x = p + tv$ describes a line through v parallel to p
term.definition: False. The effect of adding p to v is to move v in a direction parallel to the line through p and 0. So the equation $x = p + tv$ describes a line through p parallel to v.

term.word: The homogenous equation $Ax = 0$ has the trivial solution if and only if the equation has at least one free variable.
term.definition:
False

 The homogeneous equation $Ax = 0$ always has the trivial solution

term.word: The equation $Ax = 0$ gives an explicit description of its solution set.
term.definition: False. The equation $Ax = 0$ gives an implicit description of its solution set. Solving the equation amounts to finding an explicit description of its solution set.

term.word: If $b \neq 0$, can the solution set of $Ax = b$ be a plane through the​ origin?
term.definition:
No


No. If the solution set of Upper $Ax = b$ contained the​ origin, then 0 would satisfy $A0 = b$ , which is not true since b is not the zero vector.

term.word: Suppose the coefficient matrix of a system of linear equations has a pivot position in every row. Explain why the system is consistent.
term.definition: The system is consistent because the rightmost column of the augmented matrix is not a pivot column.

term.word: A general solution of a system is an explicit description of all solutions of the system.
term.definition:
True

The row reduction algorithm leads directly to an explicit description of the solution set of a linear system when the algorithm is applied to the augmented matrix of the​ system, leading to a general solution of a system.

term.word: Whenever a system has free​ variables, the solution set contains many solutions. Choose the correct answer below.
term.definition:
False

The existence of at least one solution is not related to the presence or absence of free variables. If the system is​ inconsistent, the solution set is empty.

term.word: Reducing a matrix to echelon form is called the forward phase of the row reduction process
term.definition:
True

Reducing a matrix to echelon form is called the forward phase and reducing a matrix to reduced echelon form is called the backward phase.

term.word: The pivot positions in a matrix depend on whether row interchanges are used in the row reduction process. Choose the correct answer below.
term.definition:
False

The pivot positions in a matrix are determined completely by the positions of the leading entries in the nonzero rows of any echelon form obtained from the matrix.

term.word: The echelon form of a matrix is unique.
term.definition:
False

The echelon form of a matrix is not​ unique, but the reduced echelon form is unique.

term.word: Finding a parametric description of the solution set of a linear system is the same as solving the system.
term.definition:
False

The solution set of a linear system can only be expressed using a parametric description if the system has at least one solution.

term.word: A basic variable in a linear system is a variable that corresponds to a pivot column in the coefficient matrix.
term.definition:
True

It is the definition of a basic variable

term.word: The row reduction algorithm applies only to augmented matrices for a linear system.
term.definition:
False

The algorithm applies to any​ matrix, whether or not the matrix is viewed as an augmented matrix for a linear system.

term.word: In some​ cases, a matrix may be row reduced to more than one matrix in reduced echelon​ form, using different sequences of row operations.
term.definition:
False

Each matrix is row equivalent to one and only one reduced echelon matrix.

term.word: If $A$ and $B$ are invertible $N \times N$ matriecies, then the sum $A+B$ is also invertable
11 equivalent statements about a matrix $A \in \mathbb{R}^{n \times n}$
term.definition:
1. $A$ is row equivalent to $I_{n}$
2. $A$ has n (all) pivotal columns
3. $A\vec{x} = \vec{0}$ has only the trivial solution
4. the columns of $A$ are linearly independent 
5. The linear transformation $\vec{x} \rightarrow A\vec{x}$ is one to one
6. The linear transformation $\vec{x} \rightarrow A\vec{x}$ is onto
7. The columns of $A$ span $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
8. The equation $A\vec{x} = \vec{b}$ has a solution for all $\vec{b} \in \mathbb{R}^{n}$
9. $A^{T}$ is invertible
10. There is an $n \times n$ matrix $C$ so that $CA = I_{n}$
11. There is an $n \times n$ matrix $D$ so that $DA = I_{n}$
If $A$ and $B$ are $n \times n$ matricies and $AB = I$ then $A$ and $B$ are invertable and $B = A^{-1}$ and $A = B^{-1}$
